paragraphs.title: Introduction
paragraphs.text:
%md

The following notebook uses the results from the real model, created using real hospital data, instead of the synthetic data from before. This is possible
because this level of data can't really be used for any kind of privacy breaching. In it, we compare the predictive power of our model to the predictive
power of LACE, and present the final impact on both medical care and hospital finances at the end.

paragraphs.title: Discussion
paragraphs.text:
%md

This gives us a useful look at the data. A LACE score of 12 obviously means a high chance of readmission, but beyond that we start dealing with the bigger  questions. How low can we make the default LACE score for a follow-up without overworking our hospital staff? At a score of 10, the readmission rate is just over 25%, At 9, that goes to 22%, and at 8 it becomes 20%. If we included LACE scores of 9 and up (22% chance of readmission or higher), we'd be following up after 15,609 encounters, of which only 3,788 would have been readmitted.

On the other hand, if we use the ML model with a score of 25% predicted readmission risk or higher, we have a similar number of overall encounters being followed up on, 17,202, of which 8,099 would have been readmitted.

The impact on health is fairly straightforward: better than twice as many patients who would have been readmitted are identified and can be placed in appropriate care, whether that is a simple follow-up appointment with a nurse or a referral to a skilled nursing facility.

The impact on finances depends a little on exactly which follow-up steps are taken, but for lack of more specific numbers we can use those others have used for this purpose. A follow-up, in this example, costs $200 and has a 20% chance of successfully making readmission unnecessary, and a readmission costs $5000 (in fines, fees, and general costs). The LACE-based approach would cost $3.1M and save $3.8M, which would be a reasonable expenditure. The ML approach, on the other hand, would cost $3.4M and save $8.1M, making it an excellent one.
